subString() method in JavaScript:
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>

<h2>JavaScript String Methods</h2>

<p>The substring() method extract a part of a string and returns the extracted parts in a new string:</p>

<p id="demo"></p>

<script>
let str = "Apple, Banana, Kiwi";
document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = str.substring(7,13);
</script>

</body>
</html>

output:
Banana

As the example's result, subString is much similar to slice, but subString can not accept negative value like subString(-12, -7), while slice(-12, -7) will be accepted. 
